04071nam a22005895i 9781487545079DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875450797 a10.3138/97814875450792doi  a(DE-B1597)638412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aEDU0340002bisacsh1 aBruno-Jofré, Rosa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIvan Illich Fifty Years Later :bSituating Deschooling Society in His Intellectual and Personal Journey /cJon Igelmo Zaldivar, Rosa Bruno-Jofré. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (176 p.) :b9 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- t1 Ivan Illich: From the Dalmatian Coast, through Vienna, to Rome (1926–1951) -- t2 Beyond a Unilinear Development of Illich’s Thinking: An Inquiry into Temporal Layers of Thought Forming His Critical View of the Church and the School -- t3 CIDOC as an Independent Intellectual Hub and the Conflict with the Church -- t4 Completing the Journey to Deschooling Society: A Radical Critique of Schooling -- t5 Going Back to Deschooling Society -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1971, priest, theologian, and philosopher Ivan Illich wrote Deschooling Society, a plea to liberate education from schooling and to separate schooling from the state. On the occasion of the fiftieth anniversary of its publication, Ivan Illich Fifty Years Later looks at the theological roots of Illich’s thought and the intellectual and ideological strands that contributed to his ideas. Guided by the central question of how Illich reached the point of writing Deschooling Society, the book sheds light on how Illich produced a critique of schooling that can be defined by its eclecticism. Bruno-Jofré and Igelmo Zaldívar explore how this controversial book was framed by Illich’s early neo-scholastic and anti-modern foundation, his discovery of St. Thomas through Jacques Maritain, and the existential turning points that influenced his public life and intellectual direction in moving from a critique of the Church as institution to a critique of schooling. Drawing from the interpretative theories of Quentin Skinner, Reinhart Koselleck, and William H. Sewell and from concepts such as educationalization, transnationality, and configuration, among other heuristic tools, the authors provide an original and cross-disciplinary analysis of Deschooling Society and its place in Illich’s journey.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  aCatholic.  aChristian Missionary.  aDeschooling Society.  aIntellectual.  aIvan Illich.  aLatin.  aeducation policy.  aeducation reform.  aeducation.  ahistory.  alanguage and literacy.  aphilosophy of education.1 aZaldivar, Jon Igelmo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148754507940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487545079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487545079/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles